# Styling Conventions

## CSS Modules Only

All styles MUST use CSS Modules (`.module.css` files). Never use global stylesheets.
Puck is deployed into hostile third-party environments where arbitrary CSS may exist on the page.

## SUIT CSS Naming

Class names follow the [SUIT CSS](https://suitcss.github.io) methodology:

- **Component**: `.ComponentName` (PascalCase)
- **Descendant**: `.ComponentName-descendantName` (camelCase after hyphen)
- **Modifier**: `.ComponentName--modifierName`
- **State**: `.ComponentName.is-stateName`

Examples:
- `.Puck-header`
- `.DropZone--isActive`
- `.DraggableComponent-overlay`
- `.Sidebar.is-collapsed`

## `getClassNameFactory` — The Bridge Utility

Components do NOT import `styles.ClassName` directly. Instead, use `getClassNameFactory`
(`lib/get-class-name-factory.ts`) which bridges SUIT CSS names to hashed module classes:

```tsx
import { getClassNameFactory } from "../../lib/get-class-name-factory";
import styles from "./styles.module.css";

const getClassName = getClassNameFactory("MyComponent", styles);

// Three calling modes:
getClassName()                  // → styles["MyComponent"] (root class)
getClassName("header")          // → styles["MyComponent-header"] (descendant)
getClassName({ active: true })  // → styles["MyComponent"] + styles["MyComponent--active"] (modifier)
```

Every component in `packages/core/components/` follows this pattern. Always use
`getClassNameFactory` — never access `styles[...]` directly.

## `--puck-*` CSS Custom Properties

All design tokens use a `--puck-` prefix to prevent collisions with host app variables:
- Colors: `--puck-color-*` (defined in `packages/core/styles/color.css`)
- Typography: `--puck-font-*` (defined in `packages/core/styles/typography.css`)
- Spacing: `--puck-space-*` (used inline in component CSS; not centrally defined like colors)

Always use these tokens in CSS Modules rather than hard-coded values.

## PostCSS Pipeline

The build uses `postcss` + `postcss-modules` through the shared `packages/tsup-config`.
A custom esbuild plugin in `packages/tsup-config/index.ts` intercepts `.module.css` imports,
processes them via postcss-modules (generating hashed class names + JSON mapping),
and emits both the processed CSS and a JS module exporting the class name map.

## Iframe as Runtime Isolation

The primary CSS isolation mechanism is the **iframe boundary** (`components/AutoFrame/`):
- User components render inside the iframe; editor chrome renders in the parent document.
- `CopyHostStyles` mirrors parent `<style>`/`<link>` elements into the iframe via
  `MutationObserver`, so Puck overlay styles work inside the preview.
- User component styles in the iframe do NOT leak back to the parent document.
- When `iframe.enabled = false`, there is no hard boundary — only CSS Module hashing
  and `--puck-*` prefixing protect against collisions.

## `data-*` Attribute Selectors

A few non-module `.css` files use `data-*` attribute selectors for elements Puck manages:
- `[data-puck-component]` — disables pointer events on component children in edit mode
- `[data-puck-dropzone]` — re-enables pointer events on nested drop zones
- `[data-dnd-placeholder]` — drag placeholder styling
- `[data-puck-overlay-portal]` — overlay portal pointer event overrides

These selectors are inherently scoped because only Puck adds these attributes.

## CSS-in-JS in Iframes

The core library does not use CSS-in-JS. However, user components may use Emotion or
styled-components. The `plugin-emotion-cache` package solves the problem where Emotion
injects `<style>` tags into the parent `document.head` instead of the iframe's:

```tsx
import createEmotionCachePlugin from "@puckeditor/plugin-emotion-cache";
// Creates an Emotion cache targeting the iframe's document.head
<Puck plugins={[createEmotionCachePlugin("my-key")]} />
```

This pattern (using `overrides.iframe` to redirect style injection) can be replicated
for other CSS-in-JS libraries.

## Testing with CSS Modules

In Jest tests, CSS Modules are mapped to `identity-obj-proxy` so class name lookups
return the property name as a string.
